<HEADLINE>
<P>
RED WINGS GET FEDERKO, MCKEGNEY FOR OATES, MACLEAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AP 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ST. LOUIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The St. Louis Blues on Thursday traded their all-time leading scorer, Bernie 
Federko, and left wing Tony McKegney to the Detroit Red Wings for center Adam 
Oates and right wing Paul MacLean. 
</P>
<P>
Federko, 33, who has played his 13-year career with the Blues, scored 1,073 
points in 923 games. He said he was sorry to leave St. Louis but looked forward 
to going to Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
"Jacques Demers is a very good coach," Federko said. "I had three of my very 
best years with the Blues when he was coaching, so I'm excited that I'm going 
to be back playing for him." 
</P>
<P>
McKegney, 31, after scoring 40 for the Blues in 1987-88, had only 25 goals and 
17 assists last season. 
</P>
<P>
Red Wing General Manager Jimmy Devellano said he needed to find replacements 
for Bob Probert and Petr Klima, who are not expected to play next season. 
</P>
<P>
Oates, 26, is coming off his best season. He had 16 goals and 62 assists for 78 
points in 1988-89. 
</P>
<P>
MacLean, 31, scored 36 goals and 35 assists for Detroit, but finished the 
season in Demers' doghouse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
